-------> Scripture (20min)

Before getting into Matthew chapter 4, let's do a quick recap of where we're coming from

In chapter 3 Matthew introduces John the Baptist. A man who is Jesus' cousin, living in the wilderness of Judea, calling for people to repent in preparation for the coming of the messiah, Jesus

The religious leaders of the time, Sadducees and Pharises, come to see John. John rebukes them and confronts them, telling them they must show genuine evidence of repentance rather than simply relying on their Abrahamic lineage

John compares his water baptism of repentance with the baptism of the incoming Jesus which will be with the Holy Spirit and fire

Jesus is baptized by John, the heavens open, the Holy Spirit descends upon Jesus like a dove and God declares "This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased"

So chapter 3 signifies the transition from John's prepatatory ministry to the public ministry of Jesus

Let's get into chapter 4

--> READ verses 1-4

So after the Holy Spirit descends upon Jesus and God declares Him as His son, we now go into a time of testing for Jesus

The Holy Spirit leads Jesus into the wilderness where he fasts for 40 days and nights

The 40 is significant here because it echoes the 40 years that the Israelites spent wandering in the wilderness 

While God doesn't tempt people to sin, he does use circumstances in our lives to test and strengthen our faith

Here, God allows satan to tempt Jesus to sin 

Matthew saying Jesus was hungry reiterates that while Jesus, as the son of God, could have done away with hunger, he chose to fully experience the intense hunger and weakness that would have come from 40 days and nights of fasting

Jesus is tempted by satan himself in a state of intense hunger and struggle

Jesus is a warrior. He's not some soft character. He chose to engage with the earthly stuggles of man and endure this period of testing

Jesus didn't cheat by circumventing the temptations with his divine powers, he endured them as a human being

Satans first tempation tells Jesus to turn stones into loaves of bread. 

Satan knows Jesus is physically weak and hungry. 

Matthew calls Satan the tempter. Satans primary weapon against humans is temptation. That goes all the way back to the first tempation in the garden of Eden where satan as a serpent, tempted Eve to eat the forbidden fruit

This first tempation by satan is interesting because on the surface it seems fairly harmless

He says "if you are the son of God" which he is, then turn these stones into loaves of bread. Jesus could have easily done that and doing so doesn't really seem like a sin

This is the evil brilliance of satan. Satan is tempting Jesus to put his own desires - the desire to eat because he's hungry, over the desire of God which was for Jesus to fast 

Satan is saying. You're the son of God, you should be able to do what you want, whenever you want, especially something as simple as eating food when you're hungry

Jesus understood that his fathers will was for him to endure and resist temptation. He knew that his purpose on earth was to do exactly as the father directed Him to do

Jesus responds to satan by quoting Deuteronomy 8 saying "man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that comes from the mouth of God"

So satans first attempt to separate Jesus from God is to convince him to disobey the father by turning stones into bread to appease his hunger

--> Read verse 5-7

Now satan wages his second attempt to tempt Jesus by taunting him saying - If you are the son of God, throw yourself off this ledge and God will command his angels to save you

Doing this would have instantly made it evident who Jesus was as the son of God

Satan even quotes scripture - Psalm 91: 11-12 that says angels wouldn't even allow Jesus to strike his foot on a stone - to try and convince Jesus to jump off the ledge and be saved by angels

Satan is tempting Jesus with an offer to bypass his suffering on the cross because a public miracle like this may have accelerated the process of Jesus claiming the throne of Isreal

Jesus again quotes Deuteronomy and rejects the second temptation from satan, saying "you shall not put the Lord your God to the test"

--> Read verse 8-11

Now satan attempts this third and final temptation by taking Jesus to a very high mountain and offering him rule over all of earth. Ultimate power in return for worship

The temptations are progressive. First he targets Jesus' physical apetite knowing hes hungry after 40 days of fasting

The he tempted Jesus to test God's word and avoid the cross by demonstrating a public miracle

Finally he tempted Jesus with immediate power by skipping the incoming suffering of his crucifixion

Again, Jesus quotes Deuteronomy and this time he tells satan to "be gone", at which point satan leaves him and angels arrive who begin ministering to him

Something to note: all of the temptations of satan involved timing and the choice to prioritize self over God's plan

The choice to eat instead of remain hungry

The choice to become king without waiting and suffering on the cross through a public miracle

The choice to obtain immediate power over all of earth instead of enduring suffering and allowing time to pass before he was acknowledged as king

Satan tempts us to choose selfish desires over God's plan, and by doing so, separating us from God


--> Read verses 12-17

John is arrested and improsoned by Herod Antipas, one of the sons of Herod the great who attempted to kill Jesus when he was around 2 years old

Jesus hears of John's arrest and went to the norther region of Gallilee to avoid trouble

It seems fitting that when John, who would prepare the way for Jesus gets arrested and ends his ministry, Jesus' ministry officially begins

Jesus leaves Nazareth which is a town in central Galilee and goes to live in Capernaum, a fishing village on northern shore of Gallilee which served as the home base for Jesus' ministry in Galilee

Matthew then explains that Jesus' residence in Capernaum fulfills yet another prophesy about the jewish messiah found in old testament scripture

Matthew states this because he wants jews and gentiles to understand that Jesus is not simply a significant person, but the legitimate messiah that was written about in scripture

Jesus as the son of God, the Christ, is validated by the fulfilment of ancient prophesies

In Isaiah 9 verses 1-2, scriptures promised that a great light would emerge in the region once occupied by the tribes of Zebulun and Naphtali, neae the sea of Galilee

Isaiah said a light would shine in this dark area. Dark because of its proximity to gentiles and distance from Jerusalem

Matthew is saying that Jesus is that light

verse 17 says that Jesus now begins to preach with the same core message as John the Baptist which is a call to repent for the kingdom of heaven is near

John and Jesus both reinforce an important point: we cannot participate in God's kingdom without first repenting of our sins and changing course to follow Christ

--> Read verses 18-22

So Jesus is in full ministry mode, preaching the word of God as the messiah

Matthew now begins to introduce Jesus' disciples starting with 

As I mentioned before, Capernaum was a fishing village on the northern shore of Galilee so it makes sense that Jesus recruits fishermen to follow him, starting with Simon (called Peter) and Andrew his brother

This wasn't the first time Jesus met Peter and Andrew

Andrew was a former disciple of John the Baptist. In John's gospel (different John from John the Baptist), he tells a story in Chapter 1 verses 35 - 42 of how when John the Baptist saw Jesus he exclaimed
"Behold, the lamb of God" and from that moment Andrew understood Jesus to be the Messiah and went to get Simon to meet Jesus

Jesus saw Simon and immediately changed his name to Cephas which translated means Peter

Jesus didn't call Andrew and Peter to follow him in that first encounter 

So Jesus sees Peter and Andrew casting a fishing net and says "Follow me and I will make you fishers of men" at which point they immediately leave their net and follow him

Knowing their prior encounter and that they both already knew Jesus to be the Messiah makes their obedience more understandable. Jesus wasn't just a random guy walking around to them

Fishing for men was Jesus' way of explaining their mission which would be to make disciples of men to follow Christ

It was common back then for teachers or rabbis to recruit students who would follow the teacher in their daily life

The students would be mentored by the teacher, learn from his words, his actions and how he made choices

After Peter and Andrew, Jesus sees another pair of brothers fishing - James and John who are fishing with their father Zebedee

James and John also leave their nets and father and follow Jesus

It's not stated but from what I read, it's highly likely that James and John were also aware of Jesus and knew he was the Messiah

